Find the integer $n,$ $-90 < n < 90,$ such that $\tan n^\circ = \tan 312^\circ.$
inference:
The tangent function has a period of $180^\circ.$
Therefore, if $\tan n^\circ = \tan 312^\circ,$ then
$$n = 312 + 180k$$ for some integer $k.$
If $k = 0,$ $n = 312.$
If $k = 1,$ $n = 312 + 180 = 492,$ but $492 > 90.$
If $k = -1,$ $n = 312 - 180 = 132.$
Since $-90 < n < 90,$ we must have $k = -1.$
Then $n = 132 - 360 = -228,$ which is outside the range $-90 < n < 90.$
If $k = -2,$ $n = 312 - 360 = -48.$
Since $-90 < -48 < 90,$ we have $n = -48.$
Thus $n = 312 - 2(180) = -48.$
Final Answer: $\boxed{-48}$
ground_truth:
Since the tangent function has period $180^\circ,$
\[\tan (312^\circ - 2 \cdot 180^\circ) = \tan (-48^\circ),\]so $n = \boxed{-48}.$
